# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: find-a-grave
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] AllTrails operates on a freemium business model.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] It is accessible through a mobile app or a web browser for computers.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Users can access the app's advanced features via a subscription service called AllTrails+.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Users can register via Apple, Facebook, Google or by manually entering their name, email and password.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Once a user has registered, they will be able to search and explore trails, as well as read reviews for those trails left by other users.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Upon arriving at a trail, a user will be able to see information about the trail, track their activity, or even add new trails to the service.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Additional features are available but require users to purchase a subscription in order to access them.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] AllTrails was founded in 2010 by Russell Cook.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] It was accepted into AngelPad's inaugural class.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] This incubation period preceded its official launch in December 2010.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In 2011, AllTrails gained $400k in seed funding from 500 Global (previously 500 Startups) and 2020 Ventures.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] As of January 2012, AllTrails had reached 200,000 users.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] A major partnership between National Geographic and AllTrails was announced in early 2012.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] The partnership contributed to an increase in the app's user base and enhanced its mapping data.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] This partnership also resulted in National Geographic's Topo.com being merged and redirected to AllTrails.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] By Q4 2012, 1 million users had installed AllTrails.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In August 2016, AllTrails announced that it had acquired EveryTrail from TripAdvisor, who had formerly acquired the company in 2011.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] AllTrails was listed in the 100 Best Android Apps of 2017 by PhanDroid.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In 2018, Spectrum Equity provided $75 million in funding to AllTrails in exchange for a majority position in the company.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Ben Spero and Matt Neidlinger of Spectrum Equity joined AllTrails' board of directors.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In 2018, though the company was said to be cash flow positive, it announced a new round of funding which ultimately resulted in its acquisition.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In April of 2019, AllTrails announced the acquisition of iFootpath.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In May, AllTrails announced that the app was available in French, German and Spanish.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] Formerly, the app had only been available in English.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In July, AllTrails announced its acquisition of GPSies and Trails.com.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In December, AllTrails entered into a partnership with Rolling Strong to provide truck drivers with tools and resources aimed at promoting fitness and overall health while on the road.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] In 2020, Apple partnered with AllTrails to add hiking information to Apple Maps.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] This was largely in response to the growing popularity of outdoor activities during the global COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:find-a-grave/alltrails] These trends in behavior contributed to "8.7 million users" installing the application in 2020, which represented an "89%" increase from the previous year.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] As of 2022, the company said it had provided access to 30 billion historical records, tripling its November 2018 figure of 10 billion records.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 2018 it also reported having 3 million paying subscribers, and to have sold 18 million DNA kits to customers.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] By 2023, Ancestry was the largest provider of consumer DNA testing in the world with a network of more than 25 million users, and Ancestry DNA testing is available in 128 countries.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] As well as its main website, Ancestry operates country-specific versions for Australia, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Mexico, Sweden and the United Kingdom.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry Publishing was founded in 1983, producing genealogical data in print form, with more than 40 family history magazine titles and genealogy reference books published.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 1990, Paul Brent Allen and Dan Taggart, two Brigham Young University graduates, founded Infobases and began offering Latter-day Saints (LDS) publications on floppy disks.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 1988, Allen had worked at Folio Corporation, founded by his brother Curt and his brother-in-law Brad Pelo.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The service was initially to help members of the church to research their ancestors.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Infobases' first products were floppy disks and compact discs sold from the back seat of the founders' car.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 1994, Infobases was named among *Inc.* magazine's 500 fastest-growing companies.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Their first offering on CD was the LDS Collectors Edition, released in April 1995, selling for $299.95, which was offered in an online version in August 1995.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry officially went online with the launch of Ancestry.com in 1996.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] On January 1, 1997, Infobases' parent company, Western Standard Publishing, purchased Ancestry, Inc., publisher of *Ancestry* magazine and genealogy books.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Western Standard Publishing's CEO was Joseph A.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Cannon, one of the principal owners of Geneva Steel.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In July 1997, Allen and Taggart purchased Western Standard's interest in Ancestry, Inc.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] At the time, Brad Pelo was president and CEO of Infobases, and president of Western Standard.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Less than six months earlier, he had been president of Folio Corporation, whose digital technology Infobases was using.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In March 1997, Folio was sold to Open Market for $45 million.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The first public evidence of the change in ownership of *Ancestry* magazine came with the July/August 1997 issue, which showed a newly reorganized Ancestry, Inc., as its publisher.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] That issue's masthead also included the first use of the Ancestry.com web address.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] More growth for Infobases occurred in July 1997, when Ancestry, Inc. purchased Bookcraft, Inc., a publisher of books written by leaders and officers of the LDS Church.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Infobases had published many of Bookcraft's books as part of its LDS Collector's Library.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Pelo also announced that Ancestry's product line would be greatly expanded in both CDs and online.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Alan Ashton, a longtime investor in Infobases and founder of WordPerfect, was its chairman of the board.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Allen and Taggart began running Ancestry, Inc. independently from Infobases in July 1997, and began creating one of the largest online subscription-based genealogy database services.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In April 1999, to better focus on its Ancestry.com and MyFamily.com Internet businesses, Infobases sold the Bookcraft brand name and its catalog of print books to its major competitor in the LDS book market, Deseret Book.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Included in the sale were the rights to Infobases' LDS Collectors Library on CD.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] A year earlier, Deseret Book had released a competing product called GospeLink, and the two products were combined as a single product by Deseret Book.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The MyFamily.com website launched in December 1998, with additional free sites beginning in March 1999.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The site generated one-million registered users within its first 140 days.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The company raised more than US$90 million in venture capital from investors and changed its name on November 17, 1999, from Ancestry.com, Inc. to MyFamily.com, Inc.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Its three Internet genealogy sites were then called Ancestry.com, FamilyHistory.com, and MyFamily.com.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Sales were about US$62 million for 2002 and US$99 million for 2003.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In March 2004, the company, which had outgrown its call center in Orem, Utah, opened a new call center, which accommodated about 700 agents at a time, in Provo.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Heritage Makers was acquired by MyFamily.com in September 2005.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] On November 5, 2009, Ancestry.com became a publicly traded company on NASDAQ (symbol: ACOM), with an initial public offering of 7.4 million shares priced at $13.50 per share, underwritten by Morgan Stanley, Bank of America, Merrill Lynch, Jefferies & Company, Piper Jaffray, and BMO Capital Markets.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 2010, Ancestry sold its book publishing assets to Turner Publishing Company.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 2010, Ancestry.com expanded its domestic operations with the opening of an office in San Francisco, California, staffed with brand new engineering, product, and marketing teams geared toward developing some of Ancestry's cutting-edge technology and services.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 2011, Ancestry launched an Android and iOS app.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In December 2011, Ancestry.com moved the Social Security Death Index search behind a paywall and stopped displaying the Social Security information of people who had died within the past 10 years, because of identity theft concerns.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In March 2012, Ancestry.com acquired the collection of DNA assets from GeneTree.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In September 2012, Ancestry.com expanded its international operations with the opening of its European headquarters in Dublin, Ireland.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The Dublin office includes a new call center for international customers, as well as product, marketing, and engineering teams.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In October 2012, Ancestry.com agreed to be acquired by a private equity group consisting of Permira Advisers LLP, members of Ancestry.com's management team, including CEO Tim Sullivan and CFO Howard Hochhauser, and Spectrum Equity, for $32 per share or around $1.6 billion.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] At the same time, Ancestry.com purchased a photo digitization and sharing service called 1000Memories.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 2013, Ancestry acquired Find a Grave from Jim Tipton, who had created the original site in 1995.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry subsequently launched a redesigned version of Find a Grave in 2017.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] On July 16, 2015, Ancestry launched AncestryHealth, and announced the appointment of Cathy A.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] That year, Ancestry partnered with the Google subsidiary, Calico, to focus on longevity research and therapeutics, in an effort to investigate human heredity of lifespan.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In April 2016, GIC Private Limited (a sovereign wealth fund owned by the Government of Singapore) and Silver Lake (a private equity fund manager) bought equity stakes in Ancestry.com.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The estimated market value of Ancestry.com in 2017 was more than $3 billion.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In June 2017, Ancestry.com stated that it was migrating all of its applications and data to Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Through vintage photographs, a woman was able to document eight generations of her family, dating back to 1805, including an interracial couple.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] A controversial Ancestry.com advertisement had run on television stations in Utah, showing a slavery-era interracial couple.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The advertisement was criticized by a news correspondent for Boston radio station WBUR-FM and MSNBC, and law professor Melissa Murray, on the grounds that it romanticized slavery in the antebellum South.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In April 2019, Ancestry withdrew the advertisement with an apology.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In November 2018, Ancestry claimed to have more than 10 billion digitized records and more than three-million paying customers.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In the 2021 case of the murder of George Seitz, Ancestry.com was used to help identify the remains of a crime victim.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In August 2020, The Blackstone Group announced plans to acquire Ancestry for $4.7 billion, and in December 2020 the acquisition occurred.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In February 2021, Ancestry announced Deb Liu, a former Facebook executive, as their CEO effective March 1.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In November 2021, Ancestry announced the acquisition of French Genealogy Company Geneanet.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In March 2023, Ancestry announced that it had won a contract to digitize more than 3 million British Army service records, which it would release from 2024 through 2029.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In February 2021, the Ministry Of Defence commenced transferring 9.7 million military records for individuals with a discharge date before December 31, 1963, to The National Archives UK, its largest record transfer in the history of the organization.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry's Board of Directors selected CFO and COO Howard Hochhauser to succeed Deb Liu as the company's President & CEO effective February 1, 2025.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Hochhauser will continue to serve as a member of the Board.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The company has initiated a search for a new CFO.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] AncestryDNA is a subsidiary of Ancestry LLC.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] AncestryDNA offers a direct-to-consumer genealogical DNA test.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Consumers provide a sample of their DNA to the company for analysis.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] AncestryDNA then uses DNA sequences to infer family relationships with other Ancestry DNA users, and to infer "ancestral regions" (previously "ethnicity estimates").
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Previously, Ancestry.com also offered paternal Y-chromosome DNA and maternal mitochondrial DNA tests, but those were discontinued in June 2014.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The company describes the technical process of testing in a series of scientific white papers.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In July 2020, the company claimed that their database contained 18 million completed DNA kits bought by customers.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry DNA is commonly used for donor conceived persons to find their biological siblings and in some cases their sperm or egg donor.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The testing itself is performed by Quest Diagnostics.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] AncestryDNA offers the option to participate in their Human Diversity Project, a "scientific research project aimed at helping scientists better understand population history, population movements, and human health".
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Members can also pay an additional fee to access DNA traits, which range from predicted physical traits to limited health data.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Since 2023, Ancestry has also offered genetic testing for pets, which at the moment is limited to dogs.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The test compares the DNA to more than 400 breeds.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] On September 30, 2013, Ancestry.com announced its acquisition of Find a Grave.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Site editor Jim Tipton said of the purchase that Ancestry.com had "been linking and driving traffic to the site for several years.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Burial information is a wonderful source for people researching their family history".
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry.com launched a mobile app in March 2014.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Fold3 is a premium portal that specializes in military genealogy.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Subscribers access an online database with military records, including stories, photos, and personal documents.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] It was rebranded as Forces War Records in the British & Commonwealth nations in April 2023.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The website also features the Guion Miller Roll, an Eastern Cherokee tribal roll.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Ancestry.com acquired iArchives, Inc., and its service footnote.com, in 2010.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The purchase brought in assets including processes for digitizing microfilm.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] On August 31, 2021, Ancestry.com announced its acquisition of Geneanet.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Geneanet explains that the acquisition by Ancestry is the consequence of the failure of the Filae negotiations with the birth of a formidable competitor.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The Geneanet.org site, which must remain autonomous, indicates that it will give access to many databases indexed by Ancestry within the framework of Premium subscriptions.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Archives.com was bought by Ancestry for $100 million in 2012.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Archives.com is a genealogy website specializing in census and vital records.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] As of November 29, 2023, Archives.com claimed 11.8 billion photos, newspapers, census, and vital records in its collections.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In 2012, Ancestry spun off its digitized online newspaper components into a standalone service, Newspapers.com.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] By 2024, the site had more than 25,000 newspapers able to be searched, including some from ten different countries.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The website's principal competitor is NewspaperArchive, which claims it has online newspapers dating from 1607 worldwide, and its index in March 2024 included more than 16,000 newspapers.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Both websites have similar models for increasing their databases: striking deals with libraries, publishers and historical organizations to scan the publications for free to include in their database.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Some participants see the process of free scanning as an easier, cheaper and quicker way to get their publications online than working through the U.S. government-operated National Digital Newspaper Program.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] RootsWeb, acquired by Ancestry in June 2000, is a free genealogy community that uses online forums, mailing lists, and other resources to help people research their family history.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Users can upload GEDCOM files of their information for others to search at the WorldConnect portion of the site.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Trees uploaded to WorldConnect are searchable at both the RootsWeb and Ancestry Web sites.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] On December 20, 2017, a file containing 300,000 RootsWeb user names, passwords, and email addresses was exposed to the Internet.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The 300,000 records were from RootsWeb surname list service; 55,000 of those records were also Ancestry.com login credentials.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] By 2024, the hosted Web sites were all read-only, disabling all user logins.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] We Remember is a free online memorial platform, which was launched by Ancestry in November 2017.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] It allows users to create a space to preserve and share photos and videos about the deceased.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Forces War Records was a low cost provider of transcribed genealogical data from British sources.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Much of the content behind their paywall had simply been taken from public domain sources.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] As a consequence, there was a lack of transparency as to where they sourced their content from.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] (See Wikipedia:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 315#RfC: forces-war-records.co.uk) They came under criticism for difficulties in canceling subscriptions, with a complaint about their misleading marketing being upheld by the Advertising Standards Authority.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] The provision of service records for the first time ever, via this brand, as a consequence of the linkage with fold3, has reinvigorated the brand.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] Not only transcriptions, but also images of source documents are now available to the subscriber.
[src:find-a-grave/ancestry-com] In support of the brand being relaunched as a premium portal that specializes in military genealogy, half a million records were added to the (FWR/Fold3) portal in July 2023.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On June 21, 2016, Cablevision was acquired by European telecom conglomerate Altice.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The former Cablevision services operate under Optimum Communications which continues to operate brands Optimum Online, Optimum Voice, and Optimum TV.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In the mid-1960s, Charles Dolan built a cable system called Sterling Manhattan Cable in the borough of Manhattan and launched Home Box Office (HBO).
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] He ended up selling both the cable system and HBO to Time Life Inc.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] He used the money to start a new cable system in suburban Long Island called CableVision.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision, having changed its name from CableVision, quickly expanded by building on Long Island and acquiring smaller cable systems from other providers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision also built systems throughout the New York metro area: some of the other boroughs of New York City, New Jersey, Westchester County, and Connecticut.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In the 1980s, Cablevision also expanded into the Chicago, Boston, and Cleveland areas.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] By the mid-1990s Cablevision would offer service to 2.9 million subscribers in 19 states.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Through a series of transactions in the late 1990s, Cablevision consolidated its cable systems into three core areas: New York, Cleveland, and Boston.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Despite reducing the number of areas served, they brought the number of subscribers to 3.5 million through these transactions.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] One major transaction made at this time was with Tele-Communications Inc.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision gained 10 New York area cable systems from TCI and in exchange TCI gained 33% ownership in the company.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 1999, AT&T Corporation took over TCI thus giving them the one-third ownership in Cablevision.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 2000, Cablevision sold-off its remaining systems outside the New York area in Boston, Cleveland, and Kalamazoo, Michigan to MediaOne, Adelphia, and Charter Communications respectively.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] As part of the deal, Cablevision traded its Boston area systems for MediaOne's Hudson Valley systems.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] AT&T sold its share of Cablevision in 2001.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On June 13, 2010, Cablevision announced that it would acquire Bresnan Communications for $1.37 billion.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Bresnan provided service to about 308,000 cable subscribers in Colorado, Montana, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] This is the first time in a decade that Cablevision has owned systems outside the New York area (although Bresnan, like Cablevision, had its headquarters in the New York City suburbs).
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In May 2011, Cablevision rebranded the Bresnan systems as **Optimum West**.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On February 8, 2013, Cablevision reached an agreement to sell its Optimum West systems to Charter Communications for US$1.63 billion.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On November 23, 2013, Cablevision laid off 400 employees.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On September 17, 2015, it was announced that Patrick Drahi's European telecom conglomerate Altice would acquire Cablevision for $17.7 billion, including debt, pending regulatory approval.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The deal was approved by the FCC on May 3, 2016 and after approval from various regional regulators such as New Jersey's Board of Public Utilities and the New York Public Service Commission, closed on June 21, 2016.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Under the terms of the deal, Altice paid $34.90 in cash for each share in Cablevision and a 22% premium to the company's stock price; Altice also assumed Cablevision's debt.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The former assets of Cablevision operate as Altice USA.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 2004 and 2005, Cablevision provided funding for an advertising campaign against the proposed construction of a stadium on the West Side of Manhattan supported by the Mayor of New York City, Michael Bloomberg.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The stadium would have principally served the New York Jets, and was an essential part of New York City's failed bid for the 2012 Olympics.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision had offered a competitive bid that far exceeded the bid of the Jets for property owned by the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, where the new stadium would have been located.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The plans to build the stadium were abandoned in June 2005 when the New York State Assembly under the leadership of Speaker Sheldon Silver refused to provide state subsidies for the project.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 1998, Cablevision helped found The Lustgarten Foundation, which has become the largest private foundation dedicated solely to funding pancreatic cancer research in America.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The foundation was named after former Cablevision chairman Marc Lustgarten and has raised over $16 million.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision currently underwrites the foundation, covering all administrative and fundraising costs, allowing 100% of all donations to go directly to research programs and grants to help cure pancreatic cancer, as well as sponsoring dozens of walks/runs across the country.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The foundation is a 4-star charity on Charity Navigator, ranking at this level for its organizational and financial transparency, low administrative costs, board, and growth.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 1994, Paramount Communications (formerly Gulf+Western), the owner of Madison Square Garden, was acquired by Viacom, who in turn sold the MSG properties to Cablevision and ITT Corporation, which had 50% ownership each.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] ITT would sell its share to Cablevision three years later.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On February 9, 2010, Cablevision spun off its subsidiary Madison Square Garden, L.P. into a new company named The Madison Square Garden Company (MSG).
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Although a separate company, it was run by the Cablevision CEO, James Dolan.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] He remained an important figure in both companies until Cablevision's sale in 2016, and continues to head MSG.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The company has three divisions consisting of professional sports teams, two regional sports networks, and several entertainment venues.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] MSG controls its namesake Madison Square Garden arena in New York City, and the professional sports teams that play there: the New York Knicks and New York Rangers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The same company also owns the Hartford Wolf Pack, a Hartford, Connecticut based minor-league professional hockey team affiliated with the Rangers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] MSG also holds the TV rights for the Knicks, Rangers, New York Islanders, New Jersey Devils, Buffalo Sabres and New York Red Bulls through their cable channels MSG Network, MSG Plus (formerly FSN New York), and MSG Western New York.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision previously had the rights to the New York Yankees, New Jersey Nets and New York Mets, who left to start their own channels.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision also previously attempted to purchase the Yankees, Mets and Boston Red Sox, in part, to control their broadcast rights.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Other properties that are owned by MSG include the Beacon Theatre, The Theatre at Madison Square Garden (formerly known as Felt Forum, Paramount and WaMu Theatre), and a long-term lease to operate Radio City Music Hall.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On July 1, 2011, Cablevision spun off its subsidiary, formerly known as Rainbow Media LLC, into a new company named AMC Networks, now known today as AMC Global Media.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] It owns several national cable networks including AMC, IFC, Sundance Channel, and WE tv.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Wedding Central, a cable channel that was launched as a spin-off of WE tv in 2009, was also run by Rainbow Media.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] However, upon AMC Networks achieving its independence of Cablevision, the channel was shut down due to low ratings.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Rainbow Media also controlled Fuse TV until 2010, when ownership was transferred to Cablevision's Madison Square Garden division, now operating independently as The Madison Square Garden Company (see above).
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The Rainbow Media subsidiary of Cablevision also operated a satellite television company called Voom, which was shut down on April 30, 2005, but lived on as a series of high-definition television channels named Voom HD Networks.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] They were available on Cablevision and iO digital cable until January 21, 2009.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] However, the 15 U.S. channels were eventually also shut down due to lack of distribution prior to the spinning off of Rainbow Media from Cablevision as the independent AMC Networks.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision also owned the former SportsChannel America from its beginning in 1976 until it was dissolved into Fox Sports Net in the late 1990s.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 2007 Cablevision sold its control of FSN Bay Area and FSN New England to Comcast for $570 million.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] These were the last of their regional sports networks outside the New York area.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision acquired the New York-area electronics chain The Wiz in 1998.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Richard & Son and currently remains as a dormant subsidiary of the company only showing Wiz Deals on some P.C.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] From 1998 until April 29, 2013, Cablevision owned New York-area cinema chain Clearview Cinemas.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] It was sold to Bow Tie Cinemas of Connecticut.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On July 29, 2008, Cablevision acquired Newsday and amNewYork in a deal worth $650m.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The Dolan family maintained majority ownership of Newsday, with Altice USA having a 25% share until the properties were sold in 2023.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] From September 1988 through July 1989, Cablevision did not carry MSG Network (at the time owned by Gulf+Western, which later became Paramount Communications) over the question of whether MSG should be offered as a basic service or a premium service.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] This move also occurred as New York Yankees games on cable moved to MSG from Cablevision-owned SportsChannel.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The Cablevision position was that those who wished to pay for sports programming should shoulder the burden, not every consumer.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] This dispute ended with Cablevision offering MSG as a premium subscription service.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision did not carry most of the games of the New York Yankees in 2002, because they would not accept the price asked during the inaugural season of YES Network.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Again, at the root of the argument was who was to pay for sports programming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision wanted to offer YES as a premium service, like MSG and Fox Sports NY, where YES ownership wanted the channel on the 'Family Cable' tier.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] After a long standoff, a deal was made the following year.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] As a result, YES, along with MSG and Fox Sports NY, moved to the 'Family Cable' Tier.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Until 2012, Cablevision never carried the NFL Network, as the company stated that it would like to be able to carry NFL Sunday Ticket (which was, by contract, exclusive to DirecTV until the completion of the 2022 season) before it carries NFL Network.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] This has been criticized by New Jersey legislators.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Recently however, Cablevision purchased Bresnan Communications, a company headquartered in Purchase, New York, but which did all of its business in the Rocky Mountain region.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Because of this, the NFL Network is carried on the former Bresnan (now Optimum West) systems, but not on Optimum systems in Greater New York.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Finally, on August 16, 2012, Cablevision announced that they have reached an agreement with the NFL to carry the network on all its systems effective August 17.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision also carried the Tennis Channel for a brief period of time from October 2009 to September 2011.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision joined the NCTC in August 2009 just to carry the Tennis Channel on the premium sports package which costs extra per month.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] By joining NCTC the Tennis Channel was forced to give its signal to Cablevision.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Once the Tennis Channel's contract expired with NCTC on September 3, 2011, the Tennis Channel pulled its signal from all cable carriers unwilling to negotiate a new deal or carry the channel more widespread.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The Tennis Channel was pulled from Verizon but returned on January 17, 2012.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision has yet to make any attempt at bringing the Tennis Channel back as of June 2012.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision never carried ESPN360.com, rebranded as ESPN3.com, a broadband service of ESPN.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Also, Cablevision had yet to carry and give customers access to WatchESPN which is an app that allows customers to watch ESPN Networks when they are not at home.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] ESPN requires users to give what cable provider they subscribe to in order to watch and Cablevision had yet to agree to carry WatchESPN.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On October 4, 2012, ESPN and Cablevision announced a comprehensive distribution and carriage agreement which included access for Cablevision customers to ESPN3 and WatchESPN in addition to other Watch apps covering the Walt Disney Company's family of networks.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On November 19, Cablevision announced that ESPN3 was available to Optimum Online Customers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] A month later on December 19, WatchESPN was released to Optimum TV Customers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision, as a content provider, also engaged in a dispute with Verizon over the carriage of MSG Network and Fox Sports Net New York on its FiOS television systems.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] An agreement was reached in November 2006 (shortly after the NHL and NBA began their 2006–07 seasons) allowing FiOS to carry these channels.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] However, MSG's programming was restricted to standard-definition on FiOS systems until the 2011-12 NHL and NBA seasons, when a court order forced Cablevision to provide Verizon with the HD feeds to their sports programming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Additionally, Cablevision owned exclusive rights to the MSNBC news network in its service territory, preventing its carriage by FiOS in overlapping areas.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] However, this exclusivity ended in February 2010.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Because it was unable to reach a deal with Scripps Networks Interactive concerning retransmission fees, Scripps Networks Interactive revoked Cablevision's rights to carry the disputed channels, HGTV and the Food Network, on January 1, 2010.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision also looped a public service announcement on each affected channel and forced all of its customers' set-top boxes to channel 1999, which looped the same announcement.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision and Scripps reached an agreement, and as of January 21, 2010, the two networks were back on Cablevision systems.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The details of the agreement have not been disclosed.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On March 2, 2010, WABC-TV in New York along with Philadelphia sister station WPVI (carried in Mercer, Monmouth and Ocean counties) stated that they would pull their programming from Cablevision on March 7, 2010 (at midnight), unless a new payment structure is implemented for its network programming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision responded by citing WABC-TV and WPVI's free, over-the-air accessibility.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The removal of both stations occurred on the weekend of the 82nd Academy Awards, which was scheduled to be one of ABC's largest yearly specials, and was projected to cause a devastating blow to advertisers for the Oscars and to Cablevision itself.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On Sunday, March 7, 2010, at 12:01 am ET, both WABC and WPVI were removed from Cablevision leaving a black screen in their place, confirming the rumors that if a deal with Cablevision and ABC was not reached by midnight, the network and other Disney-owned channels would go off the air.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision began looping a public service announcement on each affected channel and forcing all of its customers' set-top boxes to channel 1999, which was looping the same announcement, much like was done when Scripps Networks pulled their cable channels' programming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Besides providing certain details of the disagreement they stated that ABC shows could be watched online through TV websites such as Hulu.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Also that day, Cablevision announced through e-mail that their entire film catalog of on-demand movies would be available without charge until midnight that evening as an apology to their customers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] At 8:50 pm that day, WABC and WPVI returned to Cablevision's programming, after a notification during the 82nd Academy Awards announced progression in "Work to complete our negotiations", and the return of ABC's programming during the negotiations.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision's contract with News Corp to carry FOX (including MyNetwork TV) expired on October 15, 2010.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The contract includes WNYW and WWOR-TV in New York and WTXF in Philadelphia.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The contract also includes the cable networks National Geographic Wild, Fox Business, and Fox Deportes (formerly Fox Sports en Español).
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Programming affected by the dispute includes the coverage of the NFL on Fox, 2010 National League Championship Series, part of the 2010 World Series, and popular shows like *American Idol* and *Glee*.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On October 16, 2010, at 12:01 am, Fox pulled all of their networks involved in the dispute from Cablevision subscribers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Because of Cablevision's dispute with Fox, Cablevision customers missed multiple new episodes of Fox network programming, multiple weeks of the NBA season, and the entire NLCS.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision looped a public service announcement on each affected channel and forcing all of its customers' set-top boxes to channel 1999, which looped the same announcement, much like was done when Scripps Networks and ABC/Disney pulled their cable channels' programming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On October 27, 2010, the same day as Game 1 of the World Series, Cablevision offered a new one-year deal to FOX, which was rejected, continuing the blackout.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision also repeatedly called on FOX to submit to binding arbitration, an offer which FOX repeatedly did not take Cablevision up on.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The channels were restored during the evening of October 30, 2010, the same day as Game 3 of the World Series.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] News Corp and Cablevision reached a deal "in principle" to restore the channels.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In February 2011, Cablevision moved the Game Show Network (GSN) from the basic tier to an add-on sports package.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In October 2011, GSN filed a lawsuit claiming that the network was being discriminated against because Cablevision gave preference to other channels that they owned (AMC Networks) which did not move.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In November 2016, a Federal Communications Commission administrative law judge that Cablevision had acted unlawfully and recommended that the FCC require Cablevision (now Altice) to carry the channel on their expanded basic tier and imposed a maximum fine of $400,000.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On August 17, 2012, without warning, Cablevision pulled stations from the Tribune Company.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The removed stations included WPIX (New York), which is carried on most Cablevision systems, WPHL (Philadelphia) on Central Jersey systems in Mercer, Monmouth and Ocean Counties, WCCT (Hartford, CT) on some Connecticut systems, and KWGN (Denver) on Optimum West systems in Colorado and Wyoming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] WTIC-TV and WGN America were initially not included in this dispute, but on August 24, Tribune pulled WTIC in Connecticut and WGN from Cablevision's Connecticut and Optimum West systems.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Like the dispute with Time Warner Cable and Hearst Television, these channels were replaced with other cable offerings.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In a statement, Cablevision said that "The bankrupt Tribune Co. and the hedge funds and banks that own it, including Oaktree Capital Management, Angelo Gordon & Co. and others, are trying to solve Tribune's financial problems on the backs of Cablevision customers.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Tribune and their hedge fund owners are demanding tens of millions in new fees for WPIX and other stations they own.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Tribune, in its own statement, said that "Cablevision took this action despite our offer of an unconditional extension of the current carriage agreement with no change in terms while negotiations continued.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] To be clear, Tribune was willing to provide Cablevision subscribers access to the valuable programming on these stations while working toward a new agreement.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Tribune never made any threat to withdraw these stations or any demand that Cablevision remove them.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Tribune makes a substantial annual investment in local news, live sports and high-quality entertainment programming.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision has never compensated Tribune for the retransmission of its local stations, which are among the most highly watched channels on Cablevision's lineups.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] What we have proposed amounts to less than a penny a day per subscriber, well below what Cablevision pays to providers of less well-watched channels".
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The dispute between the two companies ended on October 26, 2012, when Cablevision reached an agreement with Tribune after Connecticut viewers complained about not seeing the first two games of the 2012 World Series.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The channels were not restored until the morning of October 27.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On January 3, 2014, WFSB, the CBS station in Hartford, CT, pulled its signal from Cablevision's Connecticut systems.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] The dispute was due to the fact that Cablevision did not want to pay Meredith Corporation, the station's owner, for Fairfield County and Litchfield County customers, because they already had the flagship CBS station, WCBS-TV from New York.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] At the time of the sale to Altice, the board of directors of Cablevision were: Charles Dolan, James Dolan, Patrick Dolan, Kristin Dolan, Marianne Dolan Weber, Rand Araskog, Frank Biondi, Charles Ferris, Richard Hochman, Victor Oristano, Thomas Reifenheiser, John R.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Ryan, Brian Sweeney, Vincent Tese, Leonard Tow.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] In 2006, the Dolan family announced a plan to purchase the company and privatize it, after a failed attempt in 2005, which would have spun off Rainbow Media as a publicly traded company.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On May 2, 2007, after repeated attempts, the Dolan family announced that a deal worth $10.6 billion had been reached for Cablevision to be taken private, but agreement was not reached with other shareholders.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] Cablevision stock trades under the ticker symbol CVC on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On November 11, 2003, the company admitted that it had misrepresented some of its finances.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] It would restate its previously reported financial statements for the first and second quarters of 2003, and would revise the quarterly financial results released that day, to reflect the impact of expenses totaling approximately $15 million that were improperly recorded in 2002 and earlier periods.
[src:find-a-grave/cablevision] On March 2, 2004, the company also said it would restate annual results for 2000 to 2002, in addition to its previously announced restatement of quarterly results in 2002 and 2003.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] Jim McKane began his genealogical quest in the early 1970s, when his father convinced him to become the custodian of the pedigree for his Lyons Clan Reunion in Chinguacousy Township, Peel County, Ontario.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] In April 2009, while volunteering as assistant webmaster of a website, he found a website archiving headstones for those who were born in County Tyrone, Northern Ireland, the home of his ancestors.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] Realizing the value of the information to genealogists and family historians, he set out to research the possibility of creating an archive for Canadian headstones.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] While there were a number of websites storing photos of gravestones, none also included the inscriptions on the gravestones.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The majority of existing sites also had either no search engine feature or very poorly constructed search features.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The result was the creation on 1 July 2009 of CanadianHeadstones.com.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The bylaws of Canadian Headstones state that the purpose of the corporation is: the corporation shall gather, archive, publish and disseminate genealogical, historical data or other records of interest to family historians, genealogists or other researchers.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] Canadian Headstones relies on volunteers, including genealogy enthusiasts, to upload photos.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The site steps a contributor through uploading a photo, editing it, choosing a county and cemetery, entering the names and inscription.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] It is then checked by a coordinator who assists the contributor to fix any problems.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The site also uses a soundex system to allow searches for sound-alike names, to account for spelling variations, typos in entries or degraded quality of older headstones.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The section of the site devoted to Quebec is available in both French and English.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] By 2012, CanadianHeadstones.com had 348,000 records submitted to the site and was growing at a rate of 10,000 entries per month.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] By 2015, the site had more than 1 million records.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The website includes a subproject to photograph gravestones of Canadian soldiers buried in cemeteries abroad, with more than 1,000 graves photographed by January 2015.
[src:find-a-grave/canadian-headstones] The site also documented Halifax Memorial at Nova Scotia's Point Pleasant Park, devoted to the Canadian sailors who died during World Wars I and II, with close-up photos of all the panels with the names of the soldiers.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] On August 1, 1979, publishers Tom Bartel and Kristin Henning debuted *Sweet Potato*, a monthly newspaper focused on the Twin Cities music scene.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] The first issue featured pop band the Cars on the cover.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] In October 1980, *Sweet Potato* went biweekly.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] On December 3, 1981, the newspaper went weekly and was renamed *City Pages*.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] *City Pages* competed for readership with the *Twin Cities Reader* until 1997, when Stern Publishing purchased *City Pages* in March and the *Twin Cities Reader* the following day, shuttering it immediately.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] Bartel and Henning left *City Pages* in the fall of 1997.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] Tom Bartel's brother Mark was named publisher after Bartel and Henning's departure.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] *City Pages* was one of seven alternative weeklies owned by Stern, including *The Village Voice*.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] After the deal's completion, New Times took the Village Voice Media name.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] In September 2012, Village Voice Media executives Scott Tobias, Christine Brennan and Jeff Mars bought Village Voice Media's papers and associated web properties from its founders and formed Voice Media Group.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] Web editor Jeff Shaw, food columnist Dara Moskowitz Grumdahl, staff writers Jonathan Kaminsky and Jeff Severns Guntzel, among others, left in 2008.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] On May 6, 2015, *City Pages* was sold to Star Tribune Media Co., publisher of the Minneapolis daily newspaper of the same name.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] Following the sale, Star Tribune Media Co. ceased publication of its competing publication, *Vita.mn*.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] On October 28, 2020, owner Star Tribune Media Co. said it would cease publication of *City Pages* immediately.
[src:find-a-grave/city-pages] The company said it could no longer sustain the newspaper after the coronavirus outbreak forced closings and downsizings of the events, nightclubs, bars and restaurants that were its chief advertisers and financial base.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Volunteers collect geographic information and the citizens/individuals can be regarded as sensors within a geographical environment that create, assemble, and disseminate geographic data provided voluntarily by the individuals.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Collaborative mapping is a special case of the larger phenomenon known as crowd sourcing, that allows citizens to be part of collaborative approach to accomplish a goal.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] The goals in collaborative mapping have a geographical aspect, e.g. having a more active role in urban planning.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Especially when data, information, knowledge is distributed in a population and an aggregation of data is not available, then collaborative mapping can bring a benefit for the citizens or activities in a community with an e-Planing Platform.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Extensions of critical and participatory approaches to geographic information systems combines software tools with a joint activities to accomplish a community goal.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Additionally, the aggregated data can be used for a Location-based service like available public transport options at the geolocation where a mobile device is currently used (GPS-sensor).
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] The relevance for the user at a specific geolocation cannot be represented with logic value in general (relevant=true/false).
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] The relevance can be represented with Fuzzy-Logic or a Fuzzy architectural spatial analysis.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Collaborative mapping applications vary depending on which feature the collaborative edition takes place: on the map itself (shared surface), or on overlays to the map.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] A very simple collaborative mapping application would just plot users' locations (social mapping or geosocial networking) or Wikipedia articles' locations (Placeopedia).
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Collaborative implies the possibility of edition by several distinct individuals so the term would tend to exclude applications where the maps are not meant for the general user to modify.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] In this kind of application, the map itself is created collaboratively by sharing a common surface.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] For example, both OpenStreetMap and WikiMapia allow for the creation of single 'points of interest', as well as linear features and areas.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Collaborative mapping and specifically surface sharing faces the same problems as revision control, namely concurrent access issues and versioning.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] In addition to these problems, collaborative maps must deal with the difficult issue of cluttering, due to the geometric constraints inherent in the media.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] One approach to this problem is using overlays, allowing to suitable use in consumer services.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Overlays group together items on a map, allowing the user of the map to toggle the overlay's visibility and thus all items contained in the overlay.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] The application uses map tiles from a third-party (for example one of the mapping APIs) and adds its own collaboratively edited overlays to them, sometimes in a wiki fashion.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] If each user's revisions are contained in an overlay, the issue of revision control and cluttering can be mitigated.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] One example of this is the accessibility platform Accessadvisr, which utilises collaborative mapping to inform persons of accessibility issues, which is perceived to be as reliable and trustworthy as professional information.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Other overlays-based collaborative mapping tools follow a different approach and focus on user centered content creation and experience.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] There users enrich maps with their own points of interest and build kind of travel books for themselves.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] At the same time users can explore overlays of other users as collaborative extension.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Humanitarian OpenStreetMap Team, based on OpenStreetMap, provides collaborative mapping support for humanitarian objectives, e.g. collaborative transportation map, epidemiological mapping for Malaria, earthquake response, or typhoon response.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] In robot navigation, 3-dimensional maps can be reconstructed collaboratively using simultaneous localization and mapping.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] If citizens or a community collects data, information (like Wikipedia, Wikiversity) then concerns come up about data quality, and specifically about its credibility.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] The same aspects of quality assurance are relevant for collaborative mapping and the possibility of vandalism.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Collaborative mapping is not restricted to the application of mobile devices but if data is captured with a mobile device the satellite navigation (like GPS is helpful to assign the current geolocation to the collected data at the geolocation.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] An image can be used e.g. as additional information of damage assessment after an earth quake.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] These sites provide general base map information and allow users to create their own content by marking locations where various events occurred or certain features exist, but aren’t already shown on the base map.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Some examples include 311-style request systems and 3D spatial technology.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] The openness for changes to the community is possible for all individuals and the community is validating changes by putting regions and location at their personal watchlist.
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Any changes in the joint repository of the mapping process are captured by a version control system- Reverting changes is possible and specific quality assured versions of specific areas can be marked as reference map for a specific area (like permanent links in Wikipedia).
[src:find-a-grave/collaborative-mapping] Blockchain can be used as integrity check of alterations or digital signature can be used to mark a certain version as "quality assured" by the institution that signed a map as digital file or digital content.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] The company was formed through acquisitions, starting with the acquisition of many of the smaller former Park papers from Media General.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Two years later, it bought several papers from Hollinger International.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In 2000, it acquired another batch of papers from the Thomson Corporation.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In 2002, CNHI paid $182 million for four daily newspapers and other non-daily publications from Ottaway Newspapers Inc., the community newspaper group of Dow Jones & Company, Inc., which had determined that these markets were not growth opportunities.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In 2006, the company acquired 6 more newspapers from Ottaway.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Ottaway used $144 million of the 2002 sale to buy *The Record* newspaper in Stockton, California, in 2003.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In September 2013, Dow Jones, which had renamed the properties as Dow Jones Local Media Group, sold the entire remaining group of 33 community newspapers to Newcastle Investment Corp. for a total of only $87 million.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In 2007, CNHI sold the *Santa Cruz Sentinel*, a former Ottaway publication, to MediaNews Group.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] As of 2006, CNHI owned 90 daily newspapers and more than 200 non-daily newspapers in 22 states.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] George Wakefield is CNHI chairman; Donna Barrett is president and CEO.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] CNHI newspapers are clustered in groups that cross-sell packages to advertisers and occasionally feature shared editorial content.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In 2009, CNHI implemented mandatory furloughs for most non-sales staff, requiring employees to take a mandatory week off without pay every quarter.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] As of 2015, these DOWOP (days off without pay) were still in effect.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Also in 2014, most CNHI newspaper sites put a paywall into place, requiring readers to subscribe after reading 5 articles.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] On June 24, 2010, the company announced that it would relocate its headquarters and about 70 jobs to Montgomery, Alabama, into the RSA Dexter Tower Building when that building is complete in late 2011 or early 2012.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Like its former headquarters in Birmingham, the new building is owned by RSA, which is the principal source of investment funding for CNHI.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Bronner, CEO of RSA, said the move will be good for the community and the company.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] *The Montgomery Advertiser* newspaper reported that Bronner was a key player in the move.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] With CNHI's Birmingham lease expiring, the decision to bring the company to Montgomery "was something that I strongly suggested," he said, according to the newspaper.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] The city and Montgomery County offered $300,000 in incentives to pay moving costs for the company.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In April 2012, along with GateHouse Media, Lee Enterprises and the E.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Scripps Company, CNHI invested in Find n Save, an online company which offers local media an online shopping platform.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] On September 25, 2017, Raycom Media announced that it would merge with CNHI.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] Both companies are already principally owned by RSA, and there were to be administrative and content synergies between the properties.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] CNHI continued to operate as a subsidiary of Raycom.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] To comply with FCC newspaper cross-ownership restrictions, CNHI was to divest papers in the seven markets where Raycom also owns television stations.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In January 2018, CNHI announced it would be moving to a regional editor system where a small number of editors would oversee coverage of regions and states.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] On June 25, 2018, Gray Television announced it would be acquiring Raycom's television assets.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] CNHI was not included in the sale to Gray and CNHI is currently seeking to sell off its newspapers, as a whole or piecemeal.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] With the completion of the purchase on January 2, 2019, the newspapers were re-organized to a direct subsidiary of RSA as Raycom ceased to exist.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In May 2024, CNHI sold ten newspapers across Alabama, Georgia and Mississippi, along with a print facility, to Carpenter Media Group.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] In January 2025, CNHI furloughed 46 employees, roughly 3% of the company's workforce.
[src:find-a-grave/community-newspaper-holdings] As can be inferred by its former name of Community Newspaper Holdings Inc., CNHI tends to acquire newspapers in smaller markets and suburbs of larger cities.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Find a Grave was created in 1995 by Jim Tipton of Salt Lake City, Utah, to support his hobby of visiting the burial sites of famous celebrities.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Tipton described his early childhood as a nerdy kid with a fascination for graves, and an interest in HTML.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Find a Grave was launched as a commercial entity in 1998, first as a trade name and then incorporated in 2000.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] In 2010, Find a Grave was expanded to include graves of non-celebrities in order to allow online visitors to pay respect to their deceased relatives or friends.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] The website contains listings of cemeteries and graves from around the world.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] American cemeteries are organized by state and county, and many cemetery records contain Google Maps (with GPS coordinates supplied by contributors) and photographs of the cemeteries and gravesites.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Individual grave records may contain dates and places of birth and death, biographical information, cemetery and plot information, photographs (of the grave marker, the individual, etc.), and contributor information.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Interment listings are added by individuals, genealogical societies, cemetery associations, and other institutions such as the International Wargraves Photography Project.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] The website is often recommended as a resource for genealogy research.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Find a Grave also maintains lists of memorials of famous persons by their "claim to fame", such as Medal of Honor recipients, religious figures, and educators.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Find a Grave exercises editorial control over these listings.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Starting from May 18, 2023, memorials became able to be marked with a "Veteran" tag.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Website policy is to remove memorials or transfer their management at the request of an immediate family member.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] In January 2022, following complaints, Find a Grave announced a new policy for memorials of recently deceased persons.
[src:find-a-grave/find-a-grave] Under the new policy, any photos or personal information, including obituaries, are hidden for three months.
